g.inkscape:label: Applying the rule to real systems

text.tspan: Applying the rule by hand can get you pretty far, but interfaces are complicated,
as are implementations. Even with the best of intentions, it's easy to make
mistakes. So, to help developers apply the rule in practice, we've developed a
tool named Commuter. Commuter helps developers systematically
evaluate the scalability of their implementations.
Commuter takes an interface specification (for example, something
like POSIX) and an implementation of that interface (for example,
Linux) and systematically finds cases where the implementation isn't
as scalable as it could be. Unlike the traditional
workload-driven approach, using Commuter doesn't require a workload.
Or for that matter, even a multicore machine.

• a xor c exists, and it is not the other rename's destination

• a and c are hard links to the same inode, a ≠ c, and b = d

A much more interesting example is fork/exec.
fork is ridiculously non-commutative. It doesn't even commute w/ memory
writes from other threads in the same process. This is unfortunate because
exec undoes most of what fork did. In fact, POSIX already has an answer to
this. They did it for embedded systems, but we like it for scalability: it's called
posix_spawn, and it combines the steps of creating a new process and loading
an image into it, so it can skip over all the stuff that makes fork so
non-commutative. And, in fact, p_s has a highly scalable implementation.
These simple interface changes translate to huge scalability wins for apps.

scalability starting with interface design, and our tool enables developers to
apply the rule to real systems and substantially improve their scalability.
